In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares May 2014 as Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month. He highlights the contributions and achievements of Asian Americans, Native Hawaiians, and Pacific Islanders in various fields such as agriculture, science, art, activism, and government leadership. The president acknowledges the historical injustices faced by these communities, including the Chinese Exclusion Act, the internment of Japanese Americans during World War II, and the discrimination faced by South Asian Americans. He mentions the establishment of the White House Initiative on AAPIs to address disparities and ensure equal access to government programs and services. President Obama also expresses his commitment to passing comprehensive immigration reform and creating a pathway to citizenship for undocumented immigrants. The proclamation encourages Americans to learn more about the history of Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders and celebrate the month with appropriate programs and activities.